# Email, Resume Parser & Encryption Utilities

## Email Service (Gmail SMTP)
```python
from utils.email_service import EmailService

email_service = EmailService()

await email_service.send_password_reset_email(
    to_email="user@example.com",
    reset_token="token",
    reset_url="https://app.example.com/auth/reset-password?token=xxx",
)
await email_service.send_verification_email(
    to_email="user@example.com",
    verification_token="token",
    verification_url="https://app.example.com/auth/verify-email?token=xxx",
)
await email_service.send_welcome_email(to_email="user@example.com", user_name="Jane Doe")
```

### When to Send the Welcome Email
- **Email/password registration**: sent after successful `POST /auth/verify-code` (not at registration time, so unverified users don't get it).
- **Google OAuth new user**: sent immediately inside the OAuth callback after the new user record is committed — Google has already verified the email. Existing Google users logging in again do **not** get a second welcome email.

### Email Design Standards (all three transactional emails must match)

All three emails — welcome, password reset, and verification code — share the same structural and visual template:

| Property | Value |
|----------|-------|
| Outer container max-width | `580px` |
| Card `border-radius` | `20px` |
| Header corner radius | `20px 20px 0 0` |
| Footer corner radius | `0 0 20px 20px` |
| Title (`h1`) font size | `28px` |
| Subtitle text | `"Companion"` |
| Greeting (`h2`) font size | `22px`, `font-weight: 600` |
| Page background | `#0d1117` |
| Card background | `#161b22` |
| Accent gradient | `linear-gradient(135deg, #00d4ff 0%, #7c3aed 100%)` |

**Never deviate from these values** when editing a single email — update all three together to keep them consistent.

### Absolute URLs in Email Templates — Always Use `settings.base_url`

Email clients (Gmail, Outlook, etc.) do **not** resolve relative URLs. Every link or button inside an email must be an absolute URL built from `self.settings.base_url`:

```python
# ✅ Correct
profile_setup_url = f"{self.settings.base_url.rstrip('/')}/profile/setup"

# ❌ Wrong — renders as http:///profile/setup in Gmail
href="/profile/setup"
```

This applies to all CTA buttons (Get Started, Reset Password, Verify Email) and any other clickable links in HTML content.

### Welcome Email — New User Destination

The "Get Started" button in the welcome email links to `/profile/setup`, not `/dashboard`. New users have not completed their profile and cannot access the full dashboard:

```python
dashboard_url = f"{self.settings.base_url.rstrip('/')}/profile/setup"
```

### Password Reset Email — Content Rules

- **No "Password Reset Request" heading** — the subject line already makes the purpose clear.
- **No fallback plain-text link** ("If the button doesn't work, copy and paste…") — the button is sufficient; the `text_content` version contains the URL separately.
- Reset link is valid for **1 hour** (`PASSWORD_RESET_TOKEN_EXPIRY_SECONDS = 3600` in `api/auth.py`).
- Old passwords **can** be reused — there is no reuse block in the reset flow (intentional consumer-UX decision).
- After a successful reset the user is redirected to `/auth/login` — they must log in manually with the new password.

### Numbered Step Circles in Email HTML

Email clients often distort CSS `border-radius` on `<td>` elements, producing ovals instead of circles. To render a reliable circular badge, always use an **inner `<div>`** with explicit `width`, `height`, and `line-height`:

```html
<td width="28" valign="top" style="padding-top: 1px;">
    <div style="width: 28px; height: 28px; line-height: 28px;
                background: linear-gradient(135deg, #00d4ff 0%, #7c3aed 100%);
                border-radius: 14px; text-align: center;
                color: #ffffff; font-weight: 700; font-size: 13px;
                font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif;">1</div>
</td>
```

Never rely on `border-radius` alone on a `<td>` for circular shapes in email HTML.

### SMTP Config
```bash
SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USERNAME=your-email@gmail.com
SMTP_PASSWORD=your-app-password   # Gmail App Password, not login password — stored as SecretStr
SMTP_FROM_EMAIL=your-email@gmail.com
SMTP_FROM_NAME=ApplyPilot
```

`SMTP_PASSWORD` is a `SecretStr` in settings. Always call `.get_secret_value()` before passing to `smtplib`:
```python
server.login(self.smtp_username, settings.smtp_password.get_secret_value())
```

### Email Header Injection Prevention
**Never** insert `to_email` or `subject` directly into MIME headers. Always sanitize first:

```python
import re
_HEADER_CONTROL_CHARS = re.compile(r"[\r\n\x00]")

def _sanitize_email_header(value: str) -> str:
    """Strip CRLF and null bytes that would allow header injection."""
    return _HEADER_CONTROL_CHARS.sub("", value)

# In send_email:
safe_to_email = _sanitize_email_header(to_email)
safe_subject  = _sanitize_email_header(subject)
message["To"]      = safe_to_email
message["Subject"] = safe_subject
server.sendmail(self.from_email, safe_to_email, message.as_string())
```

An attacker-controlled email address like `victim@x.com\r\nBcc: spam@evil.com` would inject a BCC header without sanitization.

### HTML Safety in Email Templates
All user-controlled values (names, URLs) inserted into HTML email templates must be escaped:

```python
import html

greeting = f"Hello, {html.escape(user_name)}!"
# Never: f"Hello, {user_name}!"
```

## Resume Parser
```python
from utils.resume_parser import parse_resume_from_file, SUPPORTED_EXTENSIONS
